Part One:
-Introduction-

"The reason to live, is to live life for a reason. I don't believe that humanity is searching for meaning so much as assent for our glorious and immutable impact on all that ever was and ever shall be."
-Dr. Fredrik Montaux, during an interview about his reasearch on telomere degredation and its possible impact on the concept of immortality

(Press any key to continue.)
Your vision is blurry, but things soon come into focus. A sign says, "Hyper-stasis Room". The walls are a dull grey. Metal beds with glass canopies lie in two rows, ending at a collapsed wall, where rubble has consumed the rest of the machines.

Suddenly, you notice that you're not alone. Two figures stand nearby, watching you intently. You are not initially sure if your eyes are playing tricks on you, but these creatures are clearly not human. Their deep, black eyes, like two puddles of oil, study your every move. An amphibious complexion displays their vibrant skin colors in shockingly complex patterns, like an octopus in a threat display.

(Press any key to continue.)
One of the creatures breaks formation, and approaches you. You raise your arm and slide backwards in your stasis pod, in a feeble attempt to retreat. It begins interacting with a device on its wrist. A beam of light eminating from the object casts a wide net over your body, sliding from your toes to your head.

"Hello. You can call me 'Duffy'," the creature says in perfect English.

"Don't be afraid. We're here to learn; not hurt," the second being steps forward and says."Ah, my name is Ziggy, by the way. What is yours?"

"I can't really remember my last name, but I think my first name was..."

(Type your first name)
> Ash
Ziggy says, "It is good to meet you, Ash! "

(Press any key to continue.)

You are in a Hyper-stasis room.
with Ziggy, Duffy, a broken stasis pod, a warning sign and a wall of energy.
There is only one exit in this room, which is blocked by a deep-blue energy of some kind.

You struggle to get on your feet, but Ziggy notices your disorientation, and helps you as your body adjusts to standing for the first time in decades.

When you seem to get your bearings, Ziggy goes to sit by Duffy. They begin discussing something in the strangest manner; with a series of guttural yelps and clicks.

(To proceed naturally from the Hyper-stasis Room to the next area, the user must initiate dialogue with Duffy twice. If you do not wish to read through the dialogue sequence, you may enter the command, "Skip". Be aware that this will cause you to miss out on important elements of the story.)
> talk to duffy

> talk to duffy
Talk to Duffy about...
 - You speak English?

You fumble for words as you ask, "How can I... do you... understand?"

Duffy seems to immediately know what is perplexing you. "This...," he says as he points to the device on his wrist. "It scans your body, determining your way of communicating. It slightly alters your perception of reality. We are talking in our language, but this is pursuading your mind to interpret it in a form that you can understand."

"Sanjaan Makala!" Ziggy says as her neck begins to pulsate, possibly from increased circulation of whatever fluids she might call 'blood'.

Duffy points out, "As you can see, the device is not perfect. 'Sanjaan Makala' does not have an acceptable translation. Instead, this device simply tried to make a word using your alphabet."

"This is the greatest discovery in our specie's history," Ziggy says, seemingly trying to contain excitement by covering her slim, curvy face, and those dark, dark eyes.

Duffy finally turns his head to look at her. Their body language is completely alien, but somehow familiar. You aren't sure if this, too, is the work of Duffy's device, but you detect an expression of incredulity directed at Ziggy. "It's just one," he mutters.

"And he's alive!" she replies.
You are in a Hyper-stasis room.
with Ziggy, Duffy, a broken stasis pod, a warning sign and a wall of energy.
There is only one exit in this room, which is blocked by a deep-blue energy of some kind.

(To proceed naturally from the Hyper-stasis Room to the next area, the user must initiate dialogue with Duffy twice. If you do not wish to read through the dialogue sequence, you may enter the command, "Skip". Be aware that this will cause you to miss out on important elements of the story.)
> talk to duffy

> talk to duffy
Talk to Duffy about...
 - I am just one...?

You ask, "Wait. What do you mean by, 'I am just one'?"

Duffy replies, "You are the only other known sapient species in this galaxy. You are a very special find."

Ziggy adds, "What he means to say is that you are a very rare individual. Your life is special to all of us."

"I still don't understand," you press. "Rare individual?"
Ziggy stares at Duffy for a moment, before a more sombering expression appears on her face. "You're unaware? You are the sole remaining representative of your species. Preliminary accounts suggest that humans went extinct over 100 years ago, at least.

"Does this mean that you were in stasis before the extinction event began?" Duffy asks.
"No, no," you say. "I mean... I don't know. I don't remember much of anything!"
"I feared this might happen," Duffy says. "This stasis pod's design is inferior. It seemed likely that there'd be side-effects to long term use. My initial scans suggest that memories associated with emotions may be most effected. Language and skills remain intact. Memories of your personal life could be inhibited."

Ziggy asks, "Are these effects permanent?"

"Nothing is for certain. New physiology, new set of rules to explore."
"This is crazy," you hiss under a deep breath. "I can't... I..."

The room becomes increasingly dark, and your senses dull, as you try to find your words.
"What's wrong?" you think you hear Ziggy ask, through the increasing haze in your head.

Duffy replies, "He must be losing 'consc'..."

Your brain seems to stumble, making the words sound like a low baritone mess.

"His body has been.. .for decades... 'ould' be fine."
You finallly succumb and black out.
Part 2:
-As It All Sinks In-

"Everything burns. Even my soul is on fire. Is this what it feels like -  to play God?
-Quote written in a partially-preserved journal.
You have awoken in what appears to be some sort of medical station. The aliens, Ziggy and Duffy, stand nearby. Ziggy is staring at you from a sitting position on an adjacent gourney. She jumps to her feet and makes some sort of gesture with her hand, spreading it over her chest, and then placing it as a fist over her eye.

"You are refreshed, no?" she says, with what can best be described as a smile.

"How do you feel, human?" Duffy adds.
"Horrible," you reply.
"Do you need more rest?" Ziggy asks.
"No!," you almost shout it. "I mean; what I need is answers."
"I'm afraid that you already know about as much as we do," Ziggy replies. "We haven't been on this planet long. Your stasis chamber was emitting unnatural energy. We came to investigate. That's when we began to see the extent of... the ruins."
"What's happened? I need to see!" You say, struggling to your feet. You take a few moments to regain your balance as you head directly for the door - but Duffy stops you.

"Get out of my way," you shout.
"Sit down! You are not leaving here until we allow it," Duffy shouts back. Despite his slender frame and slight build, he has an imposing stance, forcing you to back off some. Not only that, but decades of sleep have rendered you feeling particularly weak.

"And we will allow it," Ziggy continues. "All I ask is that you let us accompany you. We want answers too. We can help one another. Even protect one another."
"Because I am precious?" you reply.
"No," Ziggy says, reaching out in a surprisingly human gesture; putting her hand on your shoulder. "Because you deserve answers. And you are one of us, as far as I'm concerened."
You say, "Okay... I will do what I need to do to find answers. If you want to watch over me - you'll have to keep up."

You are in a Makeshift alien medical station.
You can see Ziggy, Duffy, an Alien Supply Crate, a laser and a strange device.

This appears to be some sort of medical structure. There are strange beds that resemble gourneys. Equipment with screens, that may be vital readings, sit near each gourney. A crane arm holds some sort of laser tool at a reasonable distance above your head.

The walls appear to be made of a dense, metallic fabric, spread loosely enough for folds and creases to form.
You can go north.
> ask duffy about key

> ask duffy about key
You ask, "That crate is locked. What's inside?"
"Just some supplies that we'll be needing."
"Do you know where the key is? I'd like to start packing for our... expedition."
"Oh," Duffy says, thinking for a moment. "I've got it right here, actually. Take what you can carry. And don't break anything."

(You have recieved the key from Duffy. You will find it in your inventory)
You are in a Makeshift alien medical station.
You can see Ziggy, Duffy, an Alien Supply Crate, a laser and a strange device.

This appears to be some sort of medical structure. There are strange beds that resemble gourneys. Equipment with screens, that may be vital readings, sit near each gourney. A crane arm holds some sort of laser tool at a reasonable distance above your head.

The walls appear to be made of a dense, metallic fabric, spread loosely enough for folds and creases to form.
You can go north.
> unlock alien supply crate

> unlock alien supply crate

The crate top begins to shift, as locks slide out of place, and the top splits into two sections that mechanically twist and fold into two tiered-shelves; possibly for sorting and organizing the items inside.
(Key removed from inventory)
> touch strange device

> touch strange device
You touch this unusual device. In an instant, your surroundings appear to change. You feel as if you are being flung into a vast void at the speed of light. A cold auru rushes over and around your limp body.

Your body comes to a jarring hault in this abyss. You are surrounded by what appears to be constellations. They are the only beyond the incredibly distant pin-pricks of ancient stars in the black fabric of the horizon.

You wonder if the device you touched in the Medical Station has killed you, and that this is the beggining of some glorious ascension. But nothing further seems to be happening, except for the randomly pulsating lights eminating from the constellations that surround you.

You cannot move a muscle in your body, and the deep cold creeps further and further up your spine, like fingers inching their way up the vertebrae.

You are in a Cold Void.
You can see a flashing lights.
> look at flashing lights

> look at flashing lights

After closer inspection, you realize that these constellations are painting a picture with the flashing stars. They are displaying detailed animals. Although, the creatures do not appear to be from Earth.

Your mind tries to process the varying images, and you subconsciously group one of the constellations with another that appears to be of a similar organism. You realize that constellations move simply because you will them to.

It appears that there is a solution to this series of constellations. It seems like there is a special order required. But the requirements of that order seem vague.

In your attempt to decipher the problem, you notice something critical in common among all of the constellations. The creatures depicted in them progressively change from one constellation to another. The puzzle seems to want you place the animals in order of their evolution. It wants to know which animal you think came first, and which evolved last in this lineage.

Somehow, you seem to know the constellation's names. It seems likely the device you touched is offering certain information to help you solve its challenge.

You hear words in the farthest reaches of your mind tell you that life on this creature's planet, like on Earth, began in the oceans. This lineage of creatures developed around the time that the vast majority of biodiversity was still in the oceans, as opposed to the land-masses.

You also notice a circle of glowing energy is forming beyond the constellations; possibly, it is a portal of some kind. A small orb appears, floating around your body. It seems to whisper, "I am here to help."
> ask for advice Help Beacon

> ask for advice Help Beacon
First, the beacon offers a note about the concept behind evolution that should help in ordering the creatures from the earliest ancestor to the most recent species:

Evolution is not to be confused with adaptation. Adaptation is the process that a creature undergoes to live in a changing environment. Adaptation occurs several times within the life of a single organism.

Evolution, on the other hand, occurs over generations. Evolution occurs not because a creature desires it to, or needs it to. Evolution simply happens. And if the evolved trait (mutation) happens to be useful, then that trait is passed on to the organism's offspring. The overwhelming majority of the time, a mutation is not beneficial to a creature, and is in fact harmful. This makes survival difficult, and passage of a nasty mutation onto offspring very unlikely.

The beacon sputters around your head, telling you that the following is a hint. "Only use this if you must." it says.

Remember the primer that stated the creature evolved at a time when the great majority of species lived in the ocean, as opposed to on the land masses. If you think critcally about that statement, then you can pose this question, and then answer it; "If most of the life is in the ocean, then what is more likely to happen; A) a species evolves from an aquatic one to a terrestrial one - to fill the empty niches available on land, or B) A species evolves from a terrestrial one to an aquatic one - to compete with the plethora of ocean-dwelling species already established.

The answer to this question is much more likely to be 'A'. That's not to say that 'B' can't or won't happen, but it is significantly less likely. With this in mind, you can much more easily order the organisms in terms of their evolution. Using logic to determine which traits would help an aquatic species as opposed to a terrestrial one, you can start ordering them in that manner.

Finally. the beacon says, "If you still have difficulty, then 'request order with help' to have me display the current constellations and their orders, which I will tell you is correct, or incorrect."

