You are in "esmond's" Pawn Shop.
You can see a painting behind counter, a register, a safe, an unusual ceramic pigeon and a scale.
It's a thrift store. There are rows of glass cases with decaying objects and oddities. Gravity has caused the glass panels to sag over such a long period of time, becoming thicker at the bottom, and thinner at the top.
You can go east.
> look at painting behind counter

> look at painting behind counter
The actual painting is a garbled mess of colors, with mold covering much of the canvas. The frame is rotting, but a metal plaque on its bottom reads,

"To Desmond, by and from Jennifer Barrister.
-A Lover's Embrace"

A small heart with an arrow piercing it is engraved into the wall next to the painting. The arrow points to behind the painting.
> flip painting behind counter

> flip painting behind counter
You flip the painting, and find a message written into the backboard.

The message says, "I knew you’d come looking for answers here first, in your shop. Find the place where the two lines converge. The place we parted every morning and reunited every evening.

But first, look in your safe. I know you never got around to using it, so I gave it a six digit code; but the code is simple. If I know you - and trust me I do - only you could figure it out.

Just remember when I told you to weigh your options carefully, before spending tens of thousands on property in the city. And you said, 'Location, location, location.' Turn the painting back when you're done. I don’t want someone… or something following you.”

> stand on scale scale

> stand on scale scale

You stand on the scale. The little, red plastic arm slides along the white background, finally coming to rest at a weight of "147". You assume that this scale must be measuring in pounds, since 147 kilograms would be absurd. At the same time, you note that your body size is not condusive with weighing 147 pounds.
> use cell phone on scale

> use cell phone on scale

You place the cell phone on the scale. The red plastic arm slides along the white background, stopping at 147; again. A scale would simply be off of the actual weight by some value - if it needed recalibration. This scale is not off. Somehow, 147 was exactly where it was supposed to be.

You say to yourself. "The phone's a valuable interface with human technology? - damn straight."
> unlock safe

> unlock safe
This safe requires a seven-digit combination.

(Enter the seven-digit combination; integers only)
> 147888
147888

You open the safe. It appears to have been cleared out, except for a cracked mirror propped against the back, and a magic 8 ball.
> take mirror

> take mirror
You take the mirror.
> take magic 8 ball

> take magic 8 ball
You take the magic 8 ball. Perhaps it has valuable answers to your many questions.
> ask about riddle

> ask about riddle
A secret slot slides open on the back of the magic 8 ball. A message is shown inside.

"8 is the magic number...

What dances above the ground, or lies just under the surface
It can fit virtually anywhere it chooses,
And can be any color it chooses at any time?
But despite what its name might imply, it is never sour.
It is smarter than you might think,
And it is always watching, like a fly on the wall."

Apparently, the magic 8 ball is expecting you to say some word. Who knows what giving the correct answer will do. The only way to know is to find out.

(When you are ready to answer the riddle, type "Answer Riddle" followed by your one-word answer.)
> answer riddle octopus

> answer riddle octopus
You attempt to solve the riddle with the answer, 'octopus'.
A snapping sound can be heard inside the magic 8 ball. The ball begins to shift and an opening appears. A small piece of paper slides from the oriface.

(magic 8 ball note has been added to you inventory)
> look at unusual ceramic pigeon

> look at unusual ceramic pigeon
It is a ceramic replica of an unusual pigeon; some species you don't recognize.

A plaque at its feet reads,

"Martha, the last of her species. Cincinnati, Ohio. 1914"

Under this is a quote.

"'Men still live who, in their youth, remember pigeons. Trees still live who, in their youth, were shaken by a living wind. But a decade hence only the oldest oaks will remember, and at long last only the hills will know.'
-Aldo Leopold"
> east

> east

You are in a Courtyard.
You can see a solar panels, a metal roofing, an iron bulkhead door, a street sign, a generator, an engraved note (iron door), a keypad (iron door), Duffy and Ziggy.

You've crossed the skeleton and are in a smalll courtyard.

To your left is a thrift store. Years of sunlight and weather have bleached the letters and worn them down to near-nothing, requiring you to afford more than a glance to read them. It says, "esmond's Pawn Shop". The first letter is missing. Probably a "D".

Straight ahead against a building wall, are solar panels and a generator, sitting under a short metal roof.

The only way to continue appears to be via a large iron bulkhead door in the building to the right. The building appears to be some sort of makeshift military complex.
You can go south, east or west.
> clean panels solar panels

> clean panels solar panels
You wipe the panels off in a delicate, but determined manner. It's not back to factory-new conditions, but its better than nothing. The question is how do you get light to reach them, with the metal roof casting a shadow.
> use mirror on solar panels

> use mirror on solar panels
You turn the mirror so that the sun reflects off of it, directing the rays onto a solar panel.

A light on the generator begins blinking yellow, before turning to a solid green. The generator seems to be powering up correctly.

However, the iron door is not reacting to the generator as it powers up.

Ziggy offers to hold the mirror in place, while you inspect the generator and iron door.
> look at generator

> look at generator
The generator is powered, but the electricty isn't making it to the door.

After a few moments of inspecting the connections, you see a severed wire bundle.
> use metal pole on bundle of severed wires

> use metal pole on bundle of severed wires
You drop the metal pole on the ground; then you carefully grab both ends of severed wire and touch the metal pole. Electricity surges through the new connection, and the door's keypad lock powers up.
> look at iron bulkhead door

> look at iron bulkhead door
The generator and metal pole are doing their jobs. The door and keypad now have power. You will need to use the keypad to open the door at this point.
> look at engraved note

> look at engraved note
An engraved note on the iron door reads,

"I had to secure this door. It's not enough to simply close it. They're too smart. And we won't be around to open it for you, if you make it this far. We're heading five clicks north to the laboratory. I left a hint for the keypad combo. You know where to find it.

-JFR"
> enter code keypad

> enter code keypad

The keypad needs a ten-digit code.

(Enter the code now; integers only)
> 2700245830

The door shifts and releases a loud thud. Gears struggle to lift the massive dead-weight, slab of iron. It slowly slides up, relinquishing control of entry into the military complex.
