 You've chosen to play the the story sequence. Please press any key to continue.

The iron door has shut behind you and the aliens, and the controls are damaged in here.

There's no going back now.

You are in the atrium of what appears to be a repurposed military complex, as large metal crates of ammunition line the far wall. There are rusted shell casings all over the floor here.

The musty, choking odor of mold and decay drifts through the stagnant air. You look up, where a large hole has been thrashed in the reinforced glass dome-ceiling.

The eerie screech of some nearby animal pierces the heavy air.

Duffy tenses, reaching for a device attached to the side of his backpack. Ziggy looks around the room, making sure the creature is indeed as far away as it sounds.

"What was that," Ziggy asks.

You wait quietly for several moments, trying to seperate the gentle, lazy  noises of your environment from anything that might be lurking in the structure.

You hear a low, rumbling creak that reverberates through the building, as it appears to be warping under years of neglect. But there is no sign of whatever made that screech.

"Doesn't matter what it is," Duffy replies. "if it ends up at the wrong end of this." Duffy readies a weapon of some sort, which begins to glow. A thin purple mist seems to whisk off the device's muzzle.

Several areas seem to be accessible from here. A massive steel door sits at the bottom of a nearby ramp, blocking the entrance to some underground facility. There's a hallway to the north and an auditorium to the east. Duffy and Ziggy are discussing something about what their scans have detected.
> look at steel bunker door

> look at steel bunker door
The door is wide; about two car lengths. It is almost fifteen feet tall, and appears to be built to withstand the heaviest ordinances. This door, unlike the one you accessed earlier, has full power. You don't see any keypad or obvious interface near this door.

"This door's security has a feedback loop vulnerability," Duffy says while  interacting with his wrist scanner. He pauses a moment. "Well maybe not a weakness - it seems to be designed this way."

"What do you mean," you ask. "Can we get through it?"

"Yes," Duffy replies. "We just need to find the power source and initiate a reset. That should cause all functioning doors to open."

"Should?" Ziggy asks.

"What did you humans once say?" Duffy asks, looking to you. "Fingers crossed?"
> east

> east

You are in an auditorium.
You can see seating, a stage, a military stockpile, a large hole, Duffy and Ziggy.
"I think we're close to that energy source I mentioned," Ziggy says.

"What makes you say that?" Duffy asks.

"My scanners - they're freaking out," she says, moving the device farther from her face; as if it were not in focus.

"Your ability to paraphrase those readings is inspiring." Duffy smiles, seemingly for the first time.

"Shoosh," she replies.

You appear to be in an auditorium. The rows of seats are mostly barren, as the fabric has long-since rotted away. Parts of the stage have collapsed. More military gear seems to have been stockpiled in here for easy access.
You can go west.
